    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Er79e] Erd\\H{o}s, Paul, Some unconventional problems in number theory. Ast\\'{e}risque (1979), 73-82.",
      "remarks": "Linnik's theorem implies that $p_n\\leq n^{O(1)}$. It is trivial that $m_n\\leq p_n$ always.\n\nIf $n=q-1$ for some prime $q$ then $m_n=p_n$. Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er79e} writes it is 'easy to show' that for infinitely many $n$ we have $m_n <p_n$, and that $m_n/n\\to \\infty$ for almost all $n$.\n\nvan Doorn in the comments has noted that if $n=2^{2k+1}$ then $m_n\\leq 2n$ and $p_n\\geq 2n+1$."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory"
    ]
  },
